PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Possible Ransomware File Extension Rename Activity Over Network Share
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect SMB rename operations over the network. The rule will detect the file extensions used during the file rename operations. After the malicious source is detected the rule will prevent any further SMB file rename and write operation from that source for the defined period of time.
Configuration Note: This rule has configuration parameters to monitor and to exclude the file extensions and IPs of the client machines doing rename operations.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Potentially Malicious RAT Traffic - III (ATT&CK T1571, T1219)
PayloadFilter2.Description: A remote access tool (or RAT) is a software used to access a remote computer often used for malicious activities. This smart rule identifies suspicious RAT traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Microsoft Windows PowerShell ISE Filename Parsing Remote Code Execution Vulnerability
PayloadFilter2.Description: Microsoft Windows PowerShell ISE is prone to remote code execution vulnerability when PowerShell ISE incorrectly parses filename. An attacker who successfully exploited the vulnerability could gain the same user rights as the current user.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Download Of A Suspicious PowerShell Script File Detected

PayloadFilter2.Name: Cisco ASA Memory Corruption Vulnerability (CVE-2016-6366)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
A buffer overflow vulnerability in the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) code of Cisco Adaptive Security Appliance (ASA), Firepower, PIX, and other software could allow an authenticated, remote attacker to cause the system to reload, or to execute arbitrary code.
Note: This rule detects exploit attempts from a Deep Security protected host. It indicates that the host is compromised and being used to carry out the attacks in the network.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Download Of Suspicious SCT File Over HTTP
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Microsoft enables scripts that are embedded in an HTML document or in a Windows Scripting Host file to access COM+ objects. An attacker can create COM+ objects in script code stored in an Extensible Markup Language (XML) files, such files are called 'scriptlets' to execute command on the remote host. This is a heuristic based rule which identifies the download of such 'scriptlets' files over HTTP.
Notes: The triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified File Protocol Handler In HTTP Location Header
PayloadFilter2.Description: Software running on Microsoft Windows that utilizes HTTP requests can be forwarded to a file:// protocol on a malicious server, which causes Windows to automatically attempt authentication via SMB to the malicious server in some circumstances. The encrypted form of the user's credentials are then logged on the malicious server. This vulnerability is alternatively known as "Redirect to SMB".

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified FTP Backdoor.Win32.Qbot.JINX Runtime Detection
PayloadFilter2.Description: Backdoor.Win32.Qbot.JINX is a bot agent that targets the Windows platform. This malware collects a plethora of information from the infected system and sends it to a remote server. Moreover, it steals login credentials for different targeted systems and services. Furthermore, the malware can monitor user's online activities, inject code into target websites, steal banking credentials, download additional plugins, and provide remote access among other nefarious activities. To survive a system reboot, it creates a scheduled task.

PayloadFilter2.Description:
Alert for this DPI Filter is triggered when traffic matching a known Command and Control pattern is observed. Cobalt Strike Beacon C&C HTTP communications could be customized with what's known as malleable C2 profiles. Those profiles are meant to mimic legitimate services requests, such as, Amazon, Google and Office 365, among others, for the purpose of hiding malicious traffic. Moreover, they could be also used for emulating a known malware C&C traffic.
Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Description: FreakOut is a Backdoor that targets the Linux platform. The malware accepts commands from an IRC server to perform various types of DDoS attacks, run a reverse shell, download and execute files, brute-force telnet ports, and more.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Usage Of WMI Execute Methods - Client (ATT&CK T1047)

This DPI rule identifies the use of WMI Process command through DCERPC request. WMIC is used by malwares and exploits for lateral movement in the network.

Collected information includes, list of all running processes, OS, user and domain specific information, among others.

It is also capable to kill processes and remove itself from the infected system.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified DNS Trojan.Win32.Trickbot.Dns Traffic
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This alert is triggered when traffic matching a known Trickbot check-in request over DNS is observed. Trickbot is a banking stealer Trojan that targets the Windows platform. The malware functionality is modular, and each module is responsible for different functionality of the malware. This variant of Trickbot known as "Anchor DNS" is responsible for communicating with the C&C server over the DNS protocol. It contacts the server for the purpose of identifying itself, sending system specific information, and exfiltrating/receiving data.
Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Ransomware Lectool-1
PayloadFilter2.Description: Lectool is a Trojan from a ransomware family. This Trojan arrives on a system as a file dropped by other malware or as a file downloaded unknowingly by users when visiting malicious sites. It checks the geographical location of the affected system and also communicates to certain websites to send and receive some data. This DPI rule detects the HTTP communication between the ransomware and it's Command and Control Servers.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Windows Client Port Mapper Decoder
PayloadFilter2.Description: Remote Procedure Call (RPC) is an interprocess communication (IPC) mechanism that enables data exchange and invocation of functionality residing in a different process. A client will call the endpoint mapper (EPM) at the server to ask for a "well known" service. The server will answer the client at which port this service is available. This rule decodes the port shared by the Server using DCE/RPC Endpoint Mapper (EPM) Protocol, and help other rules for monitoring traffic on the dynamically opened port.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Fortinet FortiGate Cookie Parser Buffer Overflow Vulnerability (CVE-2016-6909)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Fortinet FortiGate is prone to a buffer-overflow vulnerability because it fails to properly bounds-check user-supplied data before copying it into an insufficiently sized buffer. Attackers can exploit this issue to execute arbitrary code in the context of the affected application. Failed exploit attempts will result in denial-of-service conditions.
Note: This rule detects exploit attempts from a Deep Security protected host. It indicates that the host is compromised and being used to carry out the attacks in the network.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Windows Port Mapper Decoder
PayloadFilter2.Description: Microsoft Remote Procedure Call (RPC) is an interprocess communication (IPC) mechanism that enables data exchange and invocation of functionality residing in a different process. A client will call the endpoint mapper (EPM) at the server to ask for a "well known" service. The server will answer the client at which port this service is available. This rule decodes the port shared by the Server using DCE/RPC Endpoint Mapper (EPM) Protocol, and helps other rules for monitoring traffic on the dynamically opened port.

PayloadFilter2.Name: TMTR-0006: BUTERAT HTTP Request
PayloadFilter2.Description: A remote access tool (or RAT) is a software used to access a remote computer often used for malicious activities. This smart rule identifies suspicious RAT traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Ransomware Cryptesla
PayloadFilter2.Description: Cryptesla (also known as TeslaCrypt) is a Trojan from a ransomware family and this Trojan arrives on a system as a file dropped by other malware or as a file downloaded unknowingly by users when visiting malicious sites. It connects to certain websites to send and receive information. This DPI rule detects such HTTP communication between the Trojan and it's Command and Control servers.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Radmin Server Remote Control Session Setup (ATT&CK T1219)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Radmin provides an interface to perform several tasks remotely, including remote shutdown, file server functionality, etc. While Famtech's Radmin is a legitimate remote administration application, it is also sometimes associated with malware.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Usage Of PAExec Command Line Tool (ATT&CK T1569.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
PAExec is a command line tool that execute processes on remote systems and redirect console application output to the local system so that these applications appear to be running locally. This rule identifies the use of PAExec tool through SMB share. PAExec is very powerful tool and used by malware and exploits for lateral movement in the network.
Configuration Note: Administrators are suggested to add trusted IP addresses in the configuration page. The rule will block all PAExec attempts unless configured.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Ransomware Lectool
PayloadFilter2.Description: Lectool is a Trojan from a ransomware family. This Trojan arrives on a system as a file dropped by other malware or as a file downloaded unknowingly by users when visiting malicious sites. It checks the geographical location of the affected system and also communicates to certain websites to send and receive some data. This DPI rule detects the HTTP communication between the ransomware and it's Command and Control Servers.

PayloadFilter2.Name: WinRM Service Detected & Powershell RCE Over HTTP - Client (ATT&CK T1021.006, T1059.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Windows Remote Management (WinRM) is the name of both a Windows service and a protocol that allows a user to interact with a remote system (e.g., run an executable, modify the Registry, modify services). This filter detects its generic usage as well as through PowerShell.

PayloadFilter2.Name: WinRM Service Detected & Powershell RCE Over HTTP (ATT&CK T1021.006, T1059.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Windows Remote Management (WinRM) is the name of both a Windows service and a protocol that allows a user to interact with a remote system (e.g., run an executable, modify the Registry, modify services). This filter detects its generic usage as well as through PowerShell.
Note: In some network environments, this rule can generate many triggers and will need further investigation to confirm an attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Executable File Uploaded On Network Share (ATT&CK T1570)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule is based on heuristics and will detect if executable file is being uploaded on a SMB share. Hence this rule should only be applied when executable files are not used over the SMB Share.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Downloading Of PowerShell Scripts Through SMB Share (ATT&CK T1059.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: PowerShell may also be used to download and run PowerShell scripts from the Internet, which can be executed from disk or in memory without touching disk. Adversaries may use PowerShell to execute malicious PowerShell scripts that may cause Damage of the system.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified TCP Meterpreter Payload
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Meterpreter is an advanced and extensible Backdoor that is stealthy and highly resilient to detection. Additionally, it is used in post-exploitation attacks as a means to establish a foothold on an infected network. Moreover, it is generated by Metasploit, the penetration testing framework. Note that Meterpreter is also known as Beacon with other adversary simulations and red team operations frameworks such as CobaltStrike and Armitage.
Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Powershell Remote Command Execution Via WinRM - HTTP (Request) (ATT&CK T1021.006, T1059.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Windows Remote Management (WinRM) is the name of both a Windows service and a protocol that allows a user to interact with a remote system (e.g., run an executable, modify the Registry, modify services).
Note: In some network environment, this rule could generate lots of trigger, therefore trigger should be investigated further to confirm attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Usage Of WMI Execute Methods - Server
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Windows Management Instrumentation Command-line (WMIC) is a command line tool that executes commands on remote systems and redirects console application output to the local system so that these applications appear to be running locally. This DPI rule identifies the use of WMI Process command through DCERPC request. WMIC is used by malwares and exploits for lateral movement in the network.
Configuration Note: A configuration option is provided to create an approved list of IP addresses that are allowed to execute WMI commands. This rule will detect WMI traffic only when the list of allowed machines has been configured. The rule does not detect traffic in the default configuration.

ConnectionType.Name: DCERPC Services
ConnectionType.Description: Remote procedure call (RPC) is a protocol that is used by the Windows and Linux (Samba) operating system. RPC provides an inter-process communication mechanism that allows a program that is running on one computer to seamlessly access services on another computer. The protocol itself is derived from the Open Software Foundation (OSF) RPC protocol.
